"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:1.2.2\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">1.2.2</span> Animal pen, stall</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">אֻרְוָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(’awerah, ’urwah, ’uryah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs5:6\">1KI 5:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr9:25\">2CH 9:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr32:28\">2CH 32:28</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">בַּיִת</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(bayith)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam6:7\">1SA 6:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam6:10\">1SA 6:10</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מַרְבֵּק</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(marbeq)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam28:24\">1SA 28:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer46:21\">JER 46:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos6:4\">AMO 6:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mal3:20\">MAL 3:20</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">רֶפֶת</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(refeth)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hab3:17\">HAB 3:17</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">φάτνη</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(fatnē)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke13:15\">LUK 13:15</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>This structure was a stall, part of a barn where animals were fed, or it was simply a customary place where animals were fed outside, often in a semi-circular enclosure. Since people normally possessed few cattle, the stalls were often near, or even inside, the house where the family lived.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>In contrast to <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.2.1 Sheep pen, sheepfold&lt;REALIA:1.2.1&gt;</a>, this enclosure was permanent and built near the dwelling of the owner of the sheep.</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam28:24\">1SA 28:24</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer46:21\">JER 46:21</a>; and <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos6:4\">AMO 6:4</a>, the Hebrew phrase <em>‘egel marbeq</em> is literally “calf of the stall,” indicating a calf that has been kept in a stall and fed until it is fat. While <em>marbeq</em> may usually be left untranslated, it is also possible to follow <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> ’s translation of the equivalent phrase in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke15:23\">LUK 15:23</a>, where it has “best calf” (compare <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> “prize calf”).</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
